  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These aren't necessarily \"laws\" in the same way that a national law passed by a parliament is, but rather international agreements, conventions, and standards that countries are expected to implement into their own national laws.\n\nHere's a breakdown of some of the key international efforts:\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** This is the primary international body setting standards to combat money laundering, terrorist financing, and the financing of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.  While not a law itself, FATF develops recommendations that countries are expected to implement. These recommendations cover:\n    *   Criminalizing money laundering and terrorist financing.\n    *   Customer due diligence and record-keeping for financial institutions.\n    *   International cooperation.\n    *   Establishing financial intelligence units (FIUs).\n    *   Supervision and regulation of financial institutions.\n    *   Transparency and beneficial ownership of legal persons and arrangements.\n\n    FATF also assesses countries' compliance with its recommendations and publishes lists of countries with deficiencies in their AML/CFT (Anti-Money Laundering/Combating the Financing of Terrorism) regimes.  Being on these lists can have serious consequences for a country's economy.\n\n*   **United Nations Conventions:** Several UN conventions address money laundering as part of broader efforts to combat transnational organized crime and drug trafficking.  Key examples include:\n    *   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):**  This convention was one of the earliest international efforts to address money laundering, focusing on the proceeds of drug trafficking.\n    *   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):**  This convention broadened the scope of money laundering offenses to include proceeds from a wider range of crimes.\n    *   **International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999):** This is specifically focused on money laundering that facilitates terrorism.\n\n*   **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank:** These institutions play a role in combating money laundering through:\n    *   **Technical assistance:**  Providing support to countries in developing and implementing AML/CFT regimes.\n    *   **Surveillance:**  Assessing countries' financial systems and identifying vulnerabilities to money laundering.\n    *   **Conditionality:**  In some cases, requiring countries to strengthen their AML/CFT regimes as a condition for receiving loans.\n\n*   **Regional Bodies:** In addition to the global efforts mentioned above, there are also regional bodies, such as the Council of Europe's Committee of Experts on the Evaluation of Anti-Money Laundering Measures and the Financing of Terrorism (MONEYVAL), that work to combat money laundering within specific regions.\n\n**Key Considerations:**\n\n*   **Implementation:**  The effectiveness of international AML efforts depends on how well countries implement these standards and conventions into their national laws and practices.\n*   **Cooperation:**  International cooperation is essential to combating money laundering, as illicit funds often cross borders. This includes sharing information, providing mutual legal assistance, and extraditing offenders.\n*   **Evolving Threats:**  Money launderers are constantly developing new techniques, so AML efforts must be continuously updated to address these evolving threats. This includes things like cryptocurrencies and other new technologies.\n\nIn summary, while there isn't a single \"international law\" against money laundering in the sense of a global statute, there is a robust framework of international standards, conventions, and agreements that aim to prevent, detect, and punish money laundering worldwide.  These efforts rely on cooperation between countries and effective implementation at the national level.\n",
